cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.CC. 

The paper deals with the combinatorial complexity of a face in an arrangement of curves, which is a classic problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses Davenport-Schinzel sequences, which are a well-known tool in computational geometry and combinatorics, so cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also likely. The paper involves analyzing the combinatorial structure of the arrangement, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also uses some graph-theoretic techniques, which could place it in cs.GT (Graph Theory). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the worst-case complexity of the problem, which could place it in cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
